    <text>
        <body>
            
            <div1 type="letter">
                
                <pb facs="nei.j4a.24.15-16_0001"/>
                
                <fw type="curatorial">15</fw>
                
                <fw type="letterhead">
                    <hi rend="caps">JOURNAL PRESS</hi>
                        <lb/>
                    <hi rend="italics">Printers</hi> • <hi rend="italics">Publishers</hi> • <hi rend="italics">Booksellers</hi> 
                        <lb/>
                    10 <hi rend="caps">SOUTH EIGHTH</hi>
                        <lb/>
                    Columbia, Missouri
                </fw>
                
                <opener>
                    <dateline>August 20, 1956</dateline>
                
                    <address>
                        <addrLine>Dr. John <hi rend="caps">G.</hi> Neihardt,</addrLine>
                        <addrLine>Route 6,</addrLine>
                        <addrLine>Columbia, Missouri</addrLine>
                    </address>
                    
                    <salute>Dear Dr. Neihardt:</salute>
                </opener>
                <p>Perhaps the biggest thrill and certainly one of the half hours of greatest enjoyment we have had in owning a television set was when we listened--and looked--at your half-hour yesterday afternoon! We want you to know of our appreciation of it, and we hope that more similar programs follow before too long.</p>
                
                <p>Back in High School in Nebraska Mrs. Leach and I both had, in the tenth grade, some English courses that included stu<del>x</del><add>d</add>y of your work--with a special emphasis on "The Song of H ugh Glass." Some of the assignments, especially those that called for memorizing some portions, seemed a little burdensome and boresome at the time--but during the years we have occasionally commented to each other how in our conversations have cropped out little phraseologies and thoughts that were implanted at that time.</p>
                
                <p>During the ensuing years we have read at least portions of your works as they came to us, and always with a growing appreciation.</p>
                
                <p>After being privileged to meet you here in Columbia, all this took on new meaning to us; even our brief acquaintanceship gave us, we believe, an understanding we had never had before. Hearing you speak at Kiwanis Club one noon, and again at our Church School one time, added greatly to our appreciation of those poems that in earlier years had been but "school assignments."</p>
                
                <p>But as much as we have appreciated the growing understan<del>x</del><add>d</add>ing (at least we hope it is understanding), it was a truly crowning delight for us to hear and see your program yesterday!</p>
                <closer>
                    <salute>Yours sincerely,</salute>
                    <signed>Corl A. Leach</signed>
                    <signed>Corl A. Leach</signed>
                </closer>
                
            </div1>
            
            
